# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaminos-pangasinan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/abante-pangasinan-ilokano-party] The **Abante Pangasinan Ilokano Party (API)** is a political party and party-list organization in the Philippines, primarily based in the province of Pangasinan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/abante-pangasinan-ilokano-party] It seeks to represent both Pangasinense and Ilokano communities and is active in local and national politics, particularly through participation in the House of Representatives under the party-list system.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/abante-pangasinan-ilokano-party] In the 2022 Philippine general elections, the party garnered 451,372 votes, earning one seat in the 19th congress.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/abante-pangasinan-ilokano-party] Amado Espino III, the party's president, ran for a third term as Pangasinan's governor but lost to outgoing 5th district representative Ramon Guico III.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/abante-pangasinan-ilokano-party] In the 2025 elections, the party failed to earn a seat in the House.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Adams is located in the northern part of the province.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] It is bordered by Pagudpud in the north; by Santa Praxedes, Cagayan in the northeast; by Calanasan, Apayao in the east; by Dumalneg in the west; and, by Vintar in the south.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Adams is situated 105.34 kilometres (65.46 mi) from the provincial capital Laoag, and 590.85 kilometres (367.14 mi) from the country's capital city of Manila.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] The road leading to the municipality mainly from Barangay Pancian in Pagudpud used to be accessible only to motorcycles.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Improvements thereto and new concrete bridges built by the provincial government of Ilocos Norte finally made the town accessible to all vehicles as of 2020.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Moreover, there are plans to convert the provincial road into a national highway under the Department of Public Works and Highways.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Adams' villages are far from each other, with the farthest being Sitio Bucarot, located on the side of the mountain away from the *población*.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] It takes about three hours of hiking to get there.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Sitio Bucarot is still disputed territory between Adams and Calanasan, Apayao.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Due to this, the place has government buildings from both municipalities.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Adams was composed of only one barangay, and would thus be split into three.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] NOTE: In the early 2020s, both the House of Representatives and the Senate made efforts to split the single barangay into three.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] The northeastern sitios and puroks of Barangay Adams will be turned into Barangay Bucarot while the southern sitios such as Malaggao and Sinidangan will be reinstated as Barangay Malasin, thus the italicized barangays.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] The remainder of Barangay Adams will be renamed Adan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] According to the 2024 census, the population of Adams was 2,279 people, with a density of 14 inhabitants per square kilometre or 36 inhabitants per square mile.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Adams' population is composed of a mixture of different ethnicities - Ilocanos, Yapayaos, Immallods, Kankanaeys, and Bago.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Adams, belonging to the first congressional district of the province of Ilocos Norte, is governed by a mayor designated as its local chief executive and by a municipal council as its legislative body in accordance with the Local Government Code.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] The mayor, vice mayor, and the councilors are elected directly by the people through an election which is being held every three years.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] The seal and its white background speaks of the people's simple way of living; it further suggests that their lifestyle is not blemished nor corrupted by civilization and modernization.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] The shield was derived from the Provincial Seal of Ilocos Norte.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] The mountain range and the verdant field and river show the topography of the place as a potential source of wealth and livelihood.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] The mountain ranges also symbolizes the lofty ideals and the high hopes of the people for making Adams a progressive and attractive place to live in.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Local food include *balbollosa* (wild eggplant), *ubog* (rattan shoots), chicken with cardis, *aba* (gabi), *kukutit* (crushed crablets), fried frogs, *kiwet* (eel) and salads.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] There's also *tapuey* (rice wine) and *Bugnay* (fruit wine).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/adams-ilocos-norte] Adams-Pagudpud School District Office governs all public schools in the municipality.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] The name *Agno* was derived from the fruit, mango (Tagalog: mangga), and a species of swamp tree called “cited agnus-castus”, a chaste tree used for medicinal concoctions to relieve pain and illness.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] It was known to be abundant in the area.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Over time, the name “Agno” was retained and adopted as the official name of the town.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Agno was formally established as a municipality in 1791.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] During the Spanish and early American periods, it was part of the province of Zambales.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Following the Philippine Commission's enactment of Public Act No.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] 1004 on November 30, 1903, the northern portion of Zambales, including Agno, was transferred to the province of Pangasinan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] The Municipality of Agno is characterized by rolling terrain and rainfed rice fields.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Near the poblacion, or town plaza, the road passes along the Mabini river or (Balincaguing River), which drains into the South China Sea further west.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] The town plaza is home to a centuries-old Roman Catholic church, as well as one of the first congregations of the Philippine Independent Church.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] The town shares borders with the town of Bani to the north, the town of Mabini and Alaminos to the east and with Burgos to the south.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Contrary to popular belief, the Agno River does not pass this municipality.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Agno is situated 68.34 kilometres (42.46 mi) from the provincial capital Lingayen, and 277.27 kilometres (172.29 mi) from the country's capital city of Manila.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Agno is politically subdivided into 17 barangays.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Each barangay consists of puroks and some have sitios.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] The town's main livelihood is fishing and agriculture, although a number of her sons and daughters work as doctors, physical therapist, nurses, engineers, computer programmers and accountants in numerous countries around the globe.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] On top of that, the town produces successful teachers, policemen and policewomen, and lawyers.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] During the summer months of April and May the town's market abounds with fresh fruits such as mangoes and duhat, as well as fresh catch such as tuna, flying fish, grouper, lobsters and other seafood.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] The town is home to natural attractions such as the Mabini river, the Umbrella Rocks in Sabangan, as well as several beaches, Agno Beach being the longest and most popular.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] There are several other beaches hidden along the coast such as the Macaboboni cove (which features a small cave) as well as a white beach in Barangay Gayusan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] To the southern end of Agno Beach, one can dive from a two-story-high rock amidst crashing waves and end up in a beautiful coral garden below.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] Agno, belonging to the first congressional district of the province of Pangasinan, is governed by a mayor designated as its local chief executive and by a municipal council as its legislative body in accordance with the Local Government Code.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] The Agno Schools District Office governs all educational institutions within the municipality.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agno-pangasinan] It oversees the management and operations of all private and public elementary and high schools.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The name "Agoo" is believed to have originated from a native tree locally known as *"aroo"* in Ilocano and *"agoho"* in Tagalog (*Casuarina equisetifolia*), commonly referred to as the whistling pine.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This pine-like evergreen species is known for its slender, needle-like foliage and the distinctive whistling sound produced by the wind passing through its branches.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Historically, the tree grew abundantly along the riverbanks and the forested western coastline of Agoo, playing a significant role in the town's natural landscape.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Its prevalence in the region is thought to have influenced the naming of the town.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo's administration and recorded history reach further back than most Philippine municipalities, with the town being established within the same decade that the Spanish colonizers arrived on the Island of Luzon.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The history of the settlement now known as Agoo dates back even further, with both documentary and artifactual evidence supporting the assertion that it was a major port of call for foreign traders before the town was formally founded by the Spaniards.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In its early history, Agoo served as a trading port in the northern region of Pre-Hispanic Pangasinan (modern day-Pangasinan and La Union provinces).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] It was already a coastal maritime trading center for Northwestern Luzon due to its naturally shaped coastline, which provided an excellent harbor for foreign vessels entering Lingayen Gulf.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Gold mined from the Cordillera Mountain Range, coming down from the Aringay-Tonglo-Balatok gold trail, was traded in Agoo and in its neighboring settlement, Aringay.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Evidence of trade between Agoo and China has been excavated in the form of porcelain and pottery pieces unearthed at the Catholic church site during its renovation, are now displayed across the street in the Museo de Iloko.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Japanese fishermen eventually established their first settlement in the Philippines in Agoo, passing on their fishing skills and technologies to the local fishermen.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] By the time the Spanish arrived to colonize Luzon, they noted that Agoo was already inhabited by people of the "same race as those of Pangasinan".
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The town was then originally made part of Pangasinan until the Spanish authorities decided to create a new province, La Union, by culling towns from Pangasinan and Ilocos Sur.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In 1572, Juan de Salcedo, fresh from his conquest of Southern Luzon, was ordered by Miguel Lopez de Legazpi to explore Northern Luzon and "pacify the people in it".
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In June 1572, he was traversing the Angalakan River, when he saw and attacked three Japanese ships.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] When they fled, Salcedo followed them until they landed at a Japanese settlement.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] After paying tributes, the Japanese were allowed to remain.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] These Japanese would leave when the port of Agoo was later closed, but not without first teaching the natives their methods of fish culture, rice cultivation, deerskin tanning, duck breeding, and weapons manufacturing.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] A permanent settlement was established in Agoo in 1578 when two Franciscan Missionaries, Fray Juan Bautista Lucarelli of Italy and Fray Sebastian de Baeza of Spain, constructed a thatch and bamboo church in honor of Saint Francis of Assisi.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo encompassed a vast land area that spanned the modern-day towns of Rosario, Santo Tomas, Tubao, Pugo, Aringay, Caba, Bauang, and the place called "Atuley" or present-day San Juan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo became the center of the campaign of pacification and conquest, not only of the surrounding towns that would later become La Union but of the mountain tribes in the Cordilleras as well.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The two missionaries formally proclaimed Agoo as a civic unit. naming it after the river along whose banks it was built.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] At the time, the riverbank was forested with pine-like trees locally called "*aroo*" or "*agoho*" (*Casuarina equisetifolia*, or Whistling Pine).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] During the early years of the Spanish colonial period, Agoo continued to be an important point of trade with Japan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Miguel De Loarca referred to Agoo as "El Puerto de Japon" - the Japanese Port.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Rosario Mendoza-Cortes, in her book "Pangasinan 1572-1800" notes that Agoo was the region's primary port of call for Japanese and Chinese traders - with the only other contender for the honor being Sual, Pangasinan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This was because there was a Japanese colony there.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] After all, traders at Agoo would have access to a greater number of people, and it was nearer to China and Japan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The main product traded from the area was the deer pelt, which was shipped to Japan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo's role as a port deteriorated when the Spanish closed the Philippines to foreign trade.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] When foreign trade was allowed again, the shape of the gulf had changed and it was thus Sual that became the dominant port.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Most of the town's early development can be attributed to the efforts of the Augustinian Order.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] They took over from the Franciscans and administered the town off and on throughout the Spanish occupation until the secular priests took over in 1898.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] They changed the town's patron saint to Santa Monica.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] They established a school where reading, writing, industrial works, and catechism were taught.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] They relocated the town center, laid out the streets and public buildings, and established roads leading to the nearby towns.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] To facilitate the construction of churches, public buildings, and bridges, they taught the people brick and lime making, brick-laying, and stone-quarrying.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] They introduced the "moro-moro", the singing of "pasyon", new farm implement, and new plants.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Father Aquilino Garcia constructed a church, and by the end of the 15th century, the image of *Nuestra Señora de Caridad* (Our Lady of Charity) was installed in it.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This church was destroyed in 1796 and a new one was built when the original settlement was moved to what has ever since been the town center.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The church was then claimed to be the largest and grandest in northern Luzon during that time.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Ruins are scattered throughout the town's center and some are visible at this point.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In 1661, Andres Malong of Pangasinan failed to recover La Union from the Spaniards after the Battle of Agoo.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] On October 29, 1849, Governor General Claveria issued a *promovido* to fuse the Pangasinan-Ilocos-Cordillera areas into *La Union*.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] On March 2, 1850, Governor General Antonio Maria Blanco signed the Superior Decreto of La Union (34th province from Cebu-1565), with Captain Toribio Ruiz de la Escalera as the first Gobernador Military y Politico.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Isabella II of Spain decreed the province's creation on April 18, 1854.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The new province comprised the north-western towns of Pangasinan and the towns of Ilocos Sur south of the Amburayan river.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo was the oldest town to be integrated and was listed as having a population of 6,936 people.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] During the Philippine Revolution, numerous residents of Agoo actively took part in the fight for independence from Spanish rule.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Led by General Manuel Tinio y Bondoc, a close ally of Emilio Aguinaldo, the local population engaged in battles against Spanish forces in Northern Luzon.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Philippine independence from Spain was short-lived, as the Philippine-American War soon followed.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In 1899, the town of Agoo became a focal point of resistance against American troops.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] 5, commanded by Captain Fontanilla, operated across Agoo and nearby areas such as Aringay, Tubao, Santo Tomas, and Rosario.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] These guerrilla forces employed tactics such as ambushes, sabotage, and coordinated attacks on American supply lines to disrupt enemy operations.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Their resilience and knowledge of the terrain made them formidable opponents.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] On November 20, 1899, American forces reached La Union.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The guerrilla forces mounted a well-planned defense, causing heavy casualties among the U.S. troops.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This battle demonstrated the determination of local forces to resist foreign domination, despite the overwhelming resources of the American military.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] However, the loss of key leaders and the superior firepower of the Americans eventually led to the decline of organized resistance in the region.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] By 1901, La Union, including Agoo came under full American control.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The U.S. military government implemented strategies to suppress any remaining resistance, including strict curfews, intelligence-gathering operations, and the establishment of garrisons.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] During the 1910s, the American colonial administration began introducing several public services that would reshape the region.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] A public education system was established, with American teachers known as Thomasites arriving to teach English and promote American cultural values.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This system significantly influenced the educational framework of La Union, providing new opportunities for learning but also introducing colonial ideologies.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Public hospitals were also built, improving access to healthcare for residents, while infrastructure development, such as roads and bridges, facilitated economic growth.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Additionally, the introduction of a local governance system allowed Filipinos to participate in elections, marking the first steps toward self-governance.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] These developments brought notable changes to Agoo's social, educational, and political environment, shaping the town's transition into the modern era under American occupation.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo, along with the towns of Caba, La Union and Bauang, La Union were the first places the Japanese invasion force sought to control during the main effort to capture Luzon at the beginning of World War 2 - now known as the Japanese Invasion of Lingayen Gulf.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Capturing the three towns which were connected by a high quality road, but protected on one side by the ocean and the other by the sea, meant that the Japanese forces were easily able to establish a secure beachhead.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Once they had done so, they launched attacks against defense forces at San Fernando, La Union and Rosario, La Union, and from there they deployed southwards across the plains of Pangasinan and Tarlac to take Fort Stotsenburg in Pampanga, then Bulacan, and finally Manila.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In the early morning of 22 December 1941, Agoo was one of three beachheads taken by the invasion force of General Masaharu Homma during the Japanese Invasion of Lingayen Gulf.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Japanese 47th Infantry and 4th Tank Regiment were confronted by heavy weather, however, and were thus delayed and dispersed.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] They landed at about 7:30 A.M. on a four-mile stretch of beach all the way from Agoo to just north of Damortis.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo is thus recorded in World War II annals as one of the Japanese staging points for the Battle of Rosario.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The beginning of the 1970s marked a period of turmoil and change in the Philippines because Ferdinand Marcos had used foreign debt to fund too many public works projects just before his 1969 reelection campaign, which led to the 1969 Philippine economic crisis and the First Quarter Storm protests.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] La Union residents mostly did not speak up about the economic stresses they were experiencing, but when Marcos declared martial law in 1972, Agoo was included with the rest of the country.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Marcos' efforts to consolidate political power did not get much resistance in the La Union, including Agoo, since Marcos' use of violent methods for stifling dissent thus mostly took place in other provinces, such as nearby Abra, Kalinga, and Mountain Province.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Marcos also had strong political ties to La Union, notably Jose D.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Aspiras whom he appointed as Tourism Minister.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] He also allowed the powerful family factions (which had dominated La Union politics since before the American colonial era) to stay in place.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] But there were some Agoo natives, such as then-Davao Archbishop Antonio L.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Mabutas, who spoke against the human rights abuses during martial law.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Since Bishop Mabutas was in Davao at the time, he was aware of human rights abuses in that city, particularly the torture and killings of church workers.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] On July 23, 1945, the Municipal government, then led by Mayor Miguel Fontanilla, established South Provincial High School in response to education-oriented citizen Ramon Mabutas' calls for the establishment of a public high school.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] South Provincial High School turned Agoo into a center of education for Southern La Union and became one of the constituent state-run schools that were combined by Presidential Decree 1778 to create the Don Mariano Marcos Memorial State University in 1981.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] After the February 1986 People Power Revolution, President Corazon Aquino placed the Philippines under a revolutionary government until the 1987 Constitution of the Philippines could be ratified.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] During this time, the Municipality of Agoo was placed under the administration of OIC Mayor Antonio Q.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] At 4.26 P.M. on July 16, 1990, Agoo was hit by the 1990 Luzon earthquake, and was one of the most severely affected locales.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Basilica Minore of Our Lady of Charity was badly damaged, and the bell tower which was then the only remaining structure from the 1893 church, crashed completely.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Agoo municipal building collapsed completely, killing numerous citizens who were inside because they were in line to pay in time for the national income tax deadline for that quarter.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Numerous tombs in the municipal cemetery were fractured open.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The town gained media attention in the early 1990s for the alleged Marian apparitions of the Blessed Virgin Mary to Judiel Nieva.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Nieva reported seeing the Virgin Mary, popularly known as *Our Lady of Agoo* atop a Guava tree, a statue weeping with blood became highly sensationalized.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Religious pilgrimages among Filipino Catholics increased by the millions as people flocked to see the phenomenon.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The alleged apparition and healing events came into the attention of the Catholic Bishops' Conference of the Philippines, who in turn began an investigation and later released an ecclesiastical ruling that the apparitions were *non-supernatural in origin* in 1993.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] On June 11, 2014, then-representative Eufranio Eriguel, alongside co-authors La Union first district Rep.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Francisco Emmanuel Ortega III, filed House Bill 4644 to establish the first city in the second district by merging the municipalities of Agoo and Aringay.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The proposed city would have two districts under a city mayor and city vice mayor along with 14 councilors in the Sangguniang Panlungsod, new positions for which the former municipal officials could run despite having the terms limits of their offices.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The proposed bill sparked protests from the people of both Agoo and Aringay who did not want the merger because it would subject them to the same high local taxes as Agoo and because of concerns that Agoo and Aringay would lose their cultural identities.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The proposed merger did not push through within term of the 16th Congress.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Since 2010, Agoo has been regularly declared an election hotspot due to incidences of violence during national and local election periods.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The violence was attributed to "intense rivalry" between incumbent Congressman Eufranio Eriguel and his 2010 opposing candidate, former Rep.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Thomas Dumpit Jr., and later to clashes between the followers of Congressman Eriguel and his 2013 opponent, former Army General Mario Chan.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] A few years later in 2017, a number of drug-related incidents in Agoo came to national attention.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This resulted in the sacking of the police chief of Agoo, along with those of the Southern La Union towns of Bauang, Naguilan, and Tubao.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] On August 16, 2016, former Congressman Eriguel was included by Philippine President Rodrigo Duterte as one of the local government officials and legislators allegedly involved in illegal drug trade in his "I am sorry for my country" speech.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Eriguel and a number of other southern La Union politicians denied these allegations.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] On the evening of May 12, 2018, Eriguel was gunned down along with two of his bodyguards and one of his supporters by nine assailants in Barangay Capas after delivering a speech during a Sangguniang Kabataan meeting for the 2018 barangay elections.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] A 67-year-old candidate for Capas barangay captain was thus arrested hours later as a suspect in the assassination, while Eriguel's wife, Rep.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Sandra Eriguel, and their daughter, Mayor Stefanie Ann Eriguel, were provided with a security detail.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Along with the rest of the Philippines, Agoo was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic when it struck the Philippines in early 2020.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo was included in the lengthy Enhanced community quarantine in Luzon, and the municipality occasionally had to reimpose mask mandates once new spikes of the disease were reported, in order to prevent larger outbreaks.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] A 2023 vegetation survey of the land area alone found thriving populations of 17 plants, or which 7 were native and 4 were naturalized while only 6 were exotic, cultivated or unclassified.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Of these, the Mangrove pagatpat was the single most common species, and was identified as one of three species "likely to influence the growth and survival of other species" - the other two being the Ayangile, and the Aroo tree after which the town of Agoo is named.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] After local tensions leading up to the 2022 Philippine local elections, Frank Ong Sibuma was elected as the municipal mayor of Agoo.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Sibuma's candidacy was questioned on technicalities regarding his residency, and a long dispute had to be resolved by the Supreme Court of the Philippines in a January 24, 2023 decision which upheld Sibuma's election.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] It has a land area of 52.84 square kilometers or 20.40 square miles, which constitutes 3.52% of La Union's total area.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo is one of the southern municipalities of the province and is bordered on the north by Aringay, on the east by Tubao, which lies further up the foothills of the Cordilleras, and on the south by Sto.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The western shores of Agoo consist of a long beach facing the Lingayen Gulf and the South China Sea.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The town's topography is characterized by *hilly* and *mountainous* terrain that rises gradually eastward from the coastal plains.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Its landscape is also marked by wetlands, scrublands, and grasslands.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Mount Katayagan, the highest peak in the town, provides a watershed that supplies water for irrigation and households, and is home to biodiversity, including a closed forest with secondary-growth tropical moist deciduous forest.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Several creeks and rivers flow through the municipality, including the Agoo River.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This river, sometimes referred to by locals as the *Principe River*, in reference to the *Taytay Principe* Bridge (which literally means "the prince's bridge), which crosses it along the main highway.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Agoo River flows from the uplands in the east to its mouth at the South China Sea in the west.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Maligaya soil is a dark grayish-brown clay loam with coarse fragments of soft, powdery red and black concretions, characterized by medium compactness and a neutral to slightly alkaline pH.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Bauang soil is a dark grayish-brown clay loam with coarse fragments of highly weathered stratified shales and sandstones, with a pH ranging from strongly acidic to slightly acidic.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Annam soil is a brown clay loam with coarse fragments of partially and highly weathered rock or gravel, along with yellowish-brown iron and magnesium concretions, characterized by an extremely acidic to slightly acidic pH.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The town experiences the prevailing monsoon climate of Northern Luzon, characterized by a dry season from November to April and a wet season from May to October.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In the Philippine Statistics Authority 2024 census, recorded a total population of 65,256 persons based on the 2024 Census of Population and Housing (2024 CPH).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This marked an increase of 2,336 persons from the 63,692 recorded in the 2020 Census of Population.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The annual population growth rate (PGR) during this period was 0.76%, equivalent to about 8 additional persons per 1,000 population each year.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In 2020, San Nicolas West was the most populous barangay, accounting for 4.15% of the total municipal population.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The remaining barangays each contributed less than 3.32% of the municipal population.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] San Nicolas Sur, with 0.77% of the total population, remained the least populated barangay, as it was in 2015.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Of the total household population of 65,778 persons in 2020, males accounted for 50.56% while females comprised 49.44%, resulting in a sex ratio of 102 males for every 100 females.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] This ratio was consistent with the one recorded in 2015.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Males made up a higher percentage of the population in the 0–64 years age group, while females outnumbered males in the age group of 65 years and above.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In 2020, the median age of the population was 27.27 years, higher than the median age of 25.67 years recorded in 2015.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The largest age groups were those aged 10 to 14 years (9.88%), followed by those aged 15 to 19 years (9.46%) and 5 to 9 years (9.24%).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Males outnumbered females in the younger age groups (0–49 years), while females dominated the older age groups (50 years and above).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Among the household population aged 10 years and older in 2020, 38.11% were married, 39.11% were never married, 14.93% were in common-law or live-in arrangements, 5.22% were widowed, and 2.62% were annulled or separated.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] A small percentage, 0.01%, had unknown marital status.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Among the never-married population, 54.61% were males, and 45.39% were females.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In 2020, Agoo had 15,953 households, an increase from the 13,850 households recorded in 2015.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The average household size was 4.1 persons, a decrease from the 4.6 persons per household recorded in 2015.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The majority of the population in Agoo belongs to the Ilocano ethnolinguistic group, with smaller populations of Pangasinense, Tagalog, and indigenous groups such as the Bago and Ibaloi.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Iloco is the primary language spoken, while Filipino and English are widely used as the mediums of instruction and communication.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo is predominantly Roman Catholic, with significant numbers of people adhering to other Christian denominations, such as Iglesia ni Cristo, Protestantism, Aglipayan, Pentecostal and Jehovah's Witnesses.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The municipality also hosts smaller religious communities, including those practicing Islam and Buddhism.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] There are two schools district offices which govern the operation of educational institutions within the municipality.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] These are Agoo East Schools District Office, and Agoo West Schools District Office.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Schools District Offices oversee the management and operations of private and public elementary and high schools.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Among the household population aged 5 years and over, 24.97% had attended or completed elementary education, 40.57% had reached or completed high school, 10.29% were college undergraduates, and 17.04% held academic degrees.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Females outnumbered males among those with academic degrees (55.80% vs.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] 44.20%) and among those who pursued post-baccalaureate courses (57.81% vs.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo's literacy rate in 2020 was 98.77% among the household population aged 5 years and over.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The literacy rate was slightly higher among males, at 50.46%, compared to females, at 49.54%.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo has 18 public elementary schools, 4 public secondary schools and 1 state university mainly Don Mariano Marcos Memorial State University-South La Union Campus (DMMMSU-SLUC), providing education to children and young adults in the area.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo is a first-class municipality with a poverty incidence of 8.67% as of 2021.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The town's economy is primarily driven by agriculture, fishing, small-scale industries, and a growing focus on local businesses and tourism.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] As according to Cities and Municipalities Competitiveness Index 2023 the economy of Agoo is rated at 25% for economic dynamism.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] It ranks 16th in Local Economy Structure, showing strong economic foundations.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The municipality is 28th in the Presence of Business and Professional Organizations, indicating a good business presence.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] It ranks 38th in Increase in Employment, reflecting moderate employment growth.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Safety Compliant Business is ranked 48th, showing a reasonable level of compliance.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agoo ranks 98th in Cost of Living, indicating relative affordability.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The municipality ranks 92nd in Local Economy Size, reflecting a modest economic scale.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Productivity ranks 55th, showing average output levels.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Financial Deepening is ranked 54th, reflecting moderate financial activity.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Cost of Doing Business is ranked 57th, indicating competitive costs.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] However, Local Economy Growth is ranked 218th, showing slow economic growth.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Agriculture is the main source of livelihood for the residents of Agoo due to its vast agricultural lands.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The town's fields primarily cultivate rice, tobacco, corn, sugarcane, fruits, vegetables, and root crops.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In addition, fungiculture, the practice of cultivating mushrooms, is prevalent in the town and has been recognized as part of the municipality's One Town, One Product (OTOP) initiative.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Fishing is another key livelihood in Agoo, particularly in its coastal areas along Lingayen Gulf and the South China Sea.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Aquaculture is also a major industry in the town, with residents engaged in the cultivation of tilapia and bangus (milkfish), which are important for both local consumption and trade.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Livestock farming, particularly the raising of poultry, swine, cattle, carabao (water buffalo), and goats, is an essential part of the economy.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] These animals are raised for meat, egg, dairy, and other products, contributing significantly to both local consumption and trade within the region.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Industries such as basketry and woodcarving are also prominent in Agoo.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] These traditional crafts are part of the town's cultural heritage and provide livelihoods for local artisans.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Products like handmade baskets and wood carvings are sold in both local markets and regional outlets, supporting the town's economic activities.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] In the town proper, small businesses such as sari-sari stores, local restaurants, trading and others play an important role in the local economy.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] These businesses provide essential goods and services to the community and contribute to Agoo's economic development, with a growing emphasis on entrepreneurship and local commerce.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] Just as the national government, the municipal government of Agoo, is divided into three branches: executive, legislative, and judiciary.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The judicial branch is administered solely by the Supreme Court of the Philippines.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The LGUs have control of the executive and legislative branches.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The executive branch is composed of the mayor and the barangay captain for the barangays.Local Government Code of the Philippines, Book III, Department of the Interior and Local Government official website.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The legislative branch is composed of the Sangguniang Bayan (town assembly), Sangguniang Barangay (barangay council), and the Sangguniang Kabataan for the youth sector.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The seat of Government is vested upon the Mayor and other elected officers who hold office at the Townhall.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/agoo] The Sangguniang Bayan is the center of legislation, stationed in Agoo Municipio.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The municipality was named after Spanish governor-general Rafael María de Aguilar, who ordered the establishment of an independent civil political unit in the area on 16 July 1805.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The Municipality of Aguilar had its early beginnings as a cattle ranch founded by the Spaniards.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The place was known then as Sitio Balubad, which was then still part of the town of Binalatongan (now San Carlos).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] On the western part were the Zambales Mountains with its thick forests and verdant foliage.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] It was a hunter's paradise with deer and wild boar occasionally being spotted in the area.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The grass in the plains were succulent fare for fattening cattle and the water from the brooks and streams clear and sparkling.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] At that time, there roads were yet to be built.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] There were footpaths which were eventually expanded into roads to improve mobility and access, but the river arteries constituted the main mode of transportation in the interior towns.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Through these river systems, boats sailed from the Ilocos provinces in the north southwards to Dagupan, Calasiao, Lingayen and sometimes even as far as San Isidro de Labrador, Salasa, Aguilar and Camiling.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Worth noting was the fossiliferous riverbank in Camiling which was useful in making lime, while mineral waters consisting of ferruginous and alkaline waters were and are still found in Aguilar and Mangatarem.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] As a thriving place for cattle and bountiful rice harvests, it was natural for Aguilar to attract people from other towns to stay and settle in the place.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The early settlers prospered and lived in peace and contentment.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] When the Spaniards in Lingayen heard of this flourishing village, they sent Spanish explorers through the town of Salasa to visit the place.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Some Spanish soldiers and priest were left to organize a pueblo.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] In time, the clamor to convert the settlement into a town became popular.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] A petition was therefore, filed with the principales or municipal officials of Binalatongan to convert the village into a town.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The petition was finally favorably endorsed.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The decree establishing Aguilar as an independent civil political unit was issued on 16 July 1805 by Governor General Rafael Maria de Aguilar, after whom the town was named.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The decree in Lingayen on 1 August 1805.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] However, it was not until 19 January 1806 that the Provincial Governor of Pangasinan was able to make the trip to the sitio of Balubad, the site of the Poblacion, to carry out the provisions of the decree.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The Governor inspected the area, chose the most appropriate site on which to erect the town center and listed the people who wishes to settle in the new town, together with their places of origin.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The greatest number came from Lingayen, made up of 210 couples and 60 individuals from the "gremio de naturals" (native community) and 10 couples and 11 individuals from the "gremio de mestizos" (mestizo community).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] From the town of Salasa, there were 56 couples and 21 bachelors all of the rank of "Caylianes" (commoners), while from the town of San Carlos, there were 32 couples and 19 individuals, all "Caylianes".
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] There were also Ilocano migrants consisting of 6 couples and 24 bachelors.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Finally, there were some Negritos, consisting of both baptized Christians and Ynfieles (Non-Christians).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] All in all, the total number of inhabitants composed 401 tributes, for bachelors and unmarried women paid only half a tribute each.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The town was formally inaugurated on 9 May 1806 when the first officials were elected and given their appointments by the Alcalde Mayor.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The officials were headed by Don Francisco Zamuco as Gobernadorcillo and Don Juan Manguino as "Teniente Primero" (first lieutenant).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The Alcalde Mayor then proceeded to mark the jurisdictional limits of the new town.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] With the town of Salasa, the boundary was the river Balubad (now Sobol) from the mountain where the river originated to the river Agno, running a direct line from west to east.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] With the town of San Carlos, the boundary was the Agno River in the east and the Bunlalacao River in the south.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The necessary boundary markers were placed and operations were witnessed by the town officials of Salasa and San Carlos.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Mangatarem as a town did not yet exist, having been founded only in 1837.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Local folklores likewise maintained that Aguilar was identified with an eagle or agila that used to fly around the place at nighttime and would perch on a fence or alar when tired of flying, hence, agila and alar put together formed Aguilar.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Although the population of Aguilar was drawn from different places, the leadership of the town was furnished by the elite families, the principales who had moved from Lingayen to Aguilar in 1805.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Aguilar also had a large number of Ilocano migrants among the population.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Their tributes in fact contributed to the political viability of the new town.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] But in all these new towns, the initiative for and leadership in building the new town came from the Pangasinan native-born elite.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The Gobernadorcillo usually took charge of public works and improvements in the town.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] This included the building and repair of public structures, including churches and convents, as well as construction and repair of roads and bridges under the parish curate's supervision.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] For this purpose, the services of Caylianes were utilized.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] They were required to render 40 days of labor or Polos a year.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The Gobernadorcillo also had to procure building materials from the town if possible; if not he had to send a request for approval to the Superior Government in Manila through Alcalde Mayor.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] He must also keep clean and sanitary the casa tribunal and the public jail.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Aguilar is situated 16.16 kilometres (10.04 mi) from the provincial capital Lingayen, and 200.96 kilometres (124.87 mi) from the country's capital city of Manila.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Aguilar is politically subdivided into 16 barangays.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Because of the majority of vast farmlands in Aguilar, The major crops planted in the municipality are Rice, Corn, Vegetables, Mangoes, Luffas and other crops.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Aguilar is also engages in Poultry and Livestock Raising including Cows, Pigs, Carabaos, Goats, Chickens and Domestic Ducks.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Tourism is also a booming industry in the municipality due to the sudden growth of tourists visiting; due to this, various resorts has been established in various locations.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] Aguilar, belonging to the second congressional district of the province of Pangasinan, is governed by a mayor designated as its local chief executive and by a municipal council as its legislative body in accordance with the Local Government Code.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/aguilar-pangasinan] The Aguilar Schools District Office governs all educational institutions within the municipality.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] In 1743, the Zambal pioneers settled in what is now the seaside barangay Baleyadaan of Alaminos, with the settlement named after their leader Suyang.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] There, they built houses and a chapel dedicated to Saint Joseph.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] Due to the frequent typhoons, they resettled to the wide plains southwest of their previous area and named it *Casboran*, in reference to the plants abundant in their new settlement.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] A continued increase in population led into the creation of a new local government with its church and convent being constructed in 1768.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] A disagreement in town leadership led to the burning of the whole town including the church, with its residents fleeing in all directions.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] Survivors of the fire resettled some 5 kilometres (3 miles) from the sea and was called *Salapsap* or *Zarapzap*.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] The Augustinian Recollects, who are in charge of the area, then formally established a parish, with Toribio Raymundo as the first parish priest who would go on to serve from 1778 until 1815.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] It was then reconstructed under the helm of Manuel Busqueto from 1837 to 1849.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] The architect-engineer Maestro Cenon, who also designed the church of Aguilar, was tapped by Busqueto to design the church of Sarapsap.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] The entire town was told to contribute in rebuilding the church.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] Busqueto died after 16 years of being Sarapsap's parish priest.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] From 1849 to 1878, Jose Tornos continued the rebuilding of the new church.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] In 1857, the church was inaugurated built with stone walls, nipa roofing, a tabernacle and a niche for the church's patron, Saint Joseph.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] In 1860, Juan Alaminos y Vivar visited the town and in 1873, the town's name was changed into *Alaminos* in honor of the governor-general of the Philippines.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] Victoriano Vereciano became Alaminos' parish priest in 1879.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] A silver altar, a sanctuary light, floors made of concrete, and church bells were also added or implemented.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] Andres Romero succeeded Vereciano who died in 1893.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] Under his term, the cemetery was enlarged and the chapel was reconstructed.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] During the Philippine-American War in 1901, the Augustinian Recollects ceded the parish's administration to the local clergy.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] The church of Alaminos was elevated into a cathedral when the Diocese of Alaminos was founded in 1985.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-cathedral] Bishop Jesus Cabrera, its first bishop, spearheaded more cathedral improvements which include: installation of marble on the cathedral's altar and floor; new sacristy; constructions of Alaminos Pastoral Center and perpetual adoration chapel; and the repainting of the whole church in 1995.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] It is known for being the home of the Hundred Islands National Park, composed of 124 islands located off the coast of Barangay Lucap.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Alaminos is named after the Spanish general Juan Alaminos y Vivar, who served as Governor-General of the Philippines from 1873 to 1874 and was much loved by locals as he visited the then-town in 1860.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Previously named Sarapsap, it was renamed in his honor in 1872.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] It traces its roots to a barrio named Casborran (present-day barangay Baleyadaan), formerly part of Zambales.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] It eventually grew when people from Suyang (present-day barangay Zaragosa in Bolinao) relocated to the area in 1737.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] In 1747, Casborran became an independent town.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] In 1758, it was razed by fire due to a political and economic conflict.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] In 1764, inhabitants tried to rebuild the town, but another conflict happened, making them leave for Nansangaan (present-day Barangay Inerangan).
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Two years later, they found refuge at a plateau in what is now the *poblacion* of Alaminos and renamed it Sarapsap.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Ilocano settlers from Paoay, Ilocos Norte moved and stayed in the town, increasing the small population of the town in 1830.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] It was renamed *Alaminos* in 1872, 12 years after the visit of the future Governor-General Juan Alaminos y Vivar, who was well loved by residents, to the thriving town.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] In 1903, Alaminos was annexed by Pangasinan by virtue of Act No.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] The Communist Party of the Philippines was founded by Jose Maria Sison in the remote barangay of Dulacac on December 26, 1968.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] By virtue of Republic Act 9025, signed by President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo on March 5, 2001, Alaminos was converted into a city after 85% of the voters favored the ratification in a plebiscite held on March 28, 2001.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Alaminos was badly hit in May 2009 by Typhoon Emong which damaged many houses in the city, including the roof of the main church.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Alaminos is situated 38.14 kilometres (23.70 mi) from the provincial capital Lingayen, and 247.07 kilometres (153.52 mi) from the country's capital city of Manila.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] It also borders the towns of Bani in the northwest, Sual to the southeast, and Mabini to the southwest.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Alaminos City is politically subdivided into 39 barangays.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Pangasinan and Ilocano are the main languages of Alaminos.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Alaminos, belonging to the first congressional district of the province of Pangasinan, is governed by a mayor designated as its local chief executive and by a municipal council as its legislative body in accordance with the Local Government Code.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] The Galila Hundred Islands Festival is held from March 16 to 21 every year.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] *Galila* means “come” in the vernacular, and the festival includes the 100 Islands Adventure Race.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] Alaminos is between Sual and Mabini on the Olongapo–Bugallon Road.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] In 2009, it was announced that Alaminos Airport would be built near the city as a commercial airport for Pangasinan province.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] However, the timeline for construction of the airport has repeatedly come and gone.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] As of 2015, the project remains to be in its pendency.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] The Alaminos City Schools Division Office governs all educational institutions within the municipality.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] It oversees the management and operations of all private and public, from primary to secondary schools.
[src:alaminos-pangasinan/alaminos-pangasinan] There are three schools district offices under this division office namely, District I, District II, and District III.
